        q: `A previously healthy 38-year-old woman has become increasingly obtunded over the past 4 days. On physical examination, she has scleral icterus, ascites, and asterixis. She is afebrile, and her blood pressure is 110/55 mm Hg. Laboratory findings show a prothrombin time of 38 seconds (11–15 seconds), (INR [International normalized ratio] 3.1), serum ALT (alanine aminotransferase) of 1,854 U/L (8–20 U/L), AST (aspartate aminotransferase) of 1621 U/L (8–20 U/L), albumin of 1.8 g/dL (3.5–5.5 g/dL), and total protein of 4.8 g/dL (6.0–7.8 g/dL). Abnormal serum or blood levels of which of the following is the most likely cause of this patient’s decreased sensorium?`,
