        optionFeedback: [`Alkaline phosphatase is produced in the liver and excreted in the bile. Elevated serum levels suggest biliary obstruction (cholestasis) but are not associated with encephalopathy.`,`<!--Answers:-->Jaundice, ascites, asterixis, and elevated AST and ALT along with decreased sensorium all point to liver failure. One of the consequences of liver failure is the inability to convert ammonia (mainly produced in the intestine) into nontoxic urea, which is excreted in the urine. Increased ammonia levels correlate with encephalopathy; ammonia may impair neuronal function. `,`Amylase is a pancreatic enzyme whose levels are increased in acute pancreatitis due to spillage from necrotic pancreatic acinar epithelial cells. It has no effect on the brain.`,`Anti-HCV antibodies would be positive in cases of hepatitis C, which usually does not manifest as acute liver failure.`,`ANA is elevated in patients with lupus and other autoimmune diseases. It is not elevated in liver failure.`],
