        optionFeedback: [`Pulmonary edema occurs in heart failure, not liver disease.`,`Deep vein thrombosis, usually affecting the leg veins, results from prolonged immobility due to any cause and hypercoagulable states. This patient, by contrast, is at risk for bleeding.`,`<!--Answers:-->The firm, nodular liver indicates cirrhosis, in this case secondary to chronic viral hepatitis. The laboratory findings indicate decreased synthesis of albumin and clotting factors in the diseased liver. Splenomegaly and caput medusae (prominent veins around the umbilicus) indicate portal hypertension. One of the complications of portal hypertension is esophageal varices, which tend to bleed and cause hematemesis, especially in patients with blood coagulation abnormalities. `,`Kernicterus results from severe hyperbilirubinemia in the neonatal period (e.g., from immune hemolysis) that causes deposition of bilirubin in brain parenchyma, particularly in basal ganglia, where it is toxic.`,`Steatorrhea is excessive fat in the stool (fat malabsorption). It is caused most often by deficiency of pancreatic enzymes and celiac disease, not chronic liver disease.`],
