        q: `A 20-year-old primigravida gives birth at term to a male infant of normal weight and length following an uncomplicated pregnancy. On examination, no abnormalities are noted. Within the first week, the infant becomes mildly icteric. The infant receives phototherapy and is no longer icteric by week two. Which of the following mechanisms most likely led to this infant’s icterus?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Atresia of the common bile duct`,`Congenital infection with cytomegalovirus`,`Inherited deficiency of a canalicular transporter`,`Low hepatic glucuronosyltransferase activity`,`Maternally derived anti-Rh-mediated hemolysis`],
        optionFeedback: [`Bile duct atresia would lead to persistent obstruction and jaundice.`,`Congenital CMV infection may cause jaundice but usually with other findings indicating infection of multiple tissues (sensorineural hearing loss, chorioretinitis, and other abnormalities).`,`The classic syndrome caused by mutations affecting a bile transporter is Dubin-Johnson syndrome. In this rare disease, there is conjugated hyperbilirubinemia (direct bilirubin), and the jaundice is usually mild and does not require treatment. `,`<!--Answers:-->This child developed physiologic jaundice of the newborn, a common problem due to immaturity of the bilirubin conjugating system at birth. Bilirubin, a breakdown product of heme, is conjugated in hepatocytes with glucuronic acid by the enzyme glucuronosyltransferase (UGT1A1), producing a water-soluble form that is readily excreted in the bile. Neonates often have low levels of this enzyme, leading to accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin. Mutations affecting the enzyme are the cause of hereditary diseases: Crigler-Najar syndrome, type 1, which is usually fatal in the peripartum period; and Gilbert syndrome, which has milder symptoms but does not resolve with phototherapy.`,`In hemolytic disease of the newborn, there may be jaundice because of excessive breakdown of red cells and heme, leading to increased production of bilirubin. The most common cause of hemolytic disease of the newborn is Rh incompatibility which rarely, if ever, gives rise to jaundice in the firstborn child.`],
        optionStyleType: `st-upper-alpha`,
        answer: [3],
        ansText: `Rationale:- This child developed physiologic jaundice of the newborn, a common problem due to immaturity of the bilirubin conjugating system at birth. Bilirubin, a breakdown product of heme, is conjugated in hepatocytes with glucuronic acid by the enzyme glucuronosyltransferase (UGT1A1), producing a water-soluble form that is readily excreted in the bile. Neonates often have low levels of this enzyme, leading to accumulation of unconjugated bilirubin. Mutations affecting the enzyme are the cause of hereditary diseases: Crigler-Najar syndrome, type 1, which is usually fatal in the peripartum period; and Gilbert syndrome, which has milder symptoms but does not resolve with phototherapy.`,
