        optionFeedback: [`Clonorchis is a liver fluke (helminthic parasite) that is endemic in Asia and is a risk factor for development of cholangiocarcinoma, not HCC.`,`Hepatic adenoma is not associated with HBV, and rarely undergoes malignant transformation (usually when it acquires mutations in β-catenin).`,`HBV is not directly oncogenic and the viral genome does not integrate into the host genome to activate protooncogenes.`,`Mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes cause colon cancer, not HCC.`,`<!--Answers:-->This patient has chronic hepatitis B and a hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). Chronic hepatitis is a strong risk factor for HCC.   Although the mechanism of this association is not fully understood, it is likely that the growth factors and angiogenesis associated with chronic inflammation and repair (cell regeneration) promote hepatocyte proliferation and lead to oncogenic mutations. HCCs range from well-differentiated to highly anaplastic lesions. The better differentiated HCCs are comprised of cells that look much like normal hepatocytes and grow in structures that are distortions of normal: thickened trabecular structures (recapitulating liver cell plates. Pseudoglandular architecture can also be seen.`],
