        optionFeedback: [`Chronic red cell hemolysis (e.g., hemolytic anemias such as hereditary spherocytosis or sickle cell disease) leads to production of high levels of bilirubin from breakdown of heme, and is associated with pigment stones (the color stems from high bilirubin content); this is not associated with obesity, and the stones would be darker in color.`,`Clonorchis is a liver fluke (helminthic parasite) that is endemic in Asia and is a risk factor for development of cholangiocarcinoma, not HCC.`,`<!--Answers:-->This medical history in an obese woman is typical of cholecystitis with gallstones. Ultrasound is useful in confirming the diagnosis since pure cholesterol stones can be radiolucent. While pure cholesterol stones, which are rare, are pale yellow and round to ovoid, with increasing proportions of calcium carbonate, phosphates, and bilirubin, the stones take on a gray-white to black color and may be lamellated. The appearance of the calculi is characteristic of cholesterol stones. Oversecretion of cholesterol in the bile is a major factor in the development of these stones. `,`Renal excretion of phosphate is not associated with gallstones.`,`Fatty meals increase gallbladder contraction and force the expulsion of gallstones, causing obstruction and colic, but are not involved in the formation of the stones. `],
